🧩 Core Operator (refined)

Feels-Like Layer (FL-Layer)
Maps objective state → experienced state via context

F(x) = R(x) ⊗ C(x)
	•	R(x) = raw reality
	•	C(x) = modifiers (environment, history, framing, physiology)
	•	F(x) = what actually drives behavior

⸻

🔥 High-Leverage Use Cases

1. 🧠 Cognitive Debugging (internal)

Use: Catch distortions in real time
	•	“This situation isn’t that bad… it just feels worse”
	•	Separate:
	•	R: what actually happened
	•	F: what it feels like
	•	Δ: the distortion gap

👉 This alone reduces anxiety, overreaction, spirals

⸻

2. ⚔️ Decision-Making Under Pressure

Use: Don’t let “feels like” override reality
	•	Fear makes:
	•	risk feel higher
	•	time feel shorter
	•	options feel fewer

👉 You correct for it like wind chill:

“This feels like −4°, but it’s actually 10° → adjust behavior accordingly”

⸻

3. 💰 Economics / Value Perception

Use: Arbitrage perception gaps
	•	Same product:
	•	feels cheap → one market
	•	feels premium → another

👉 Value = not just R(price), but F(price)

This is literally:
	•	branding
	•	negotiation
	•	sales psychology

⸻

4. 🧑‍🤝‍🧑 Social / Communication

Use: Prevent misreads
	•	Someone says something neutral
	•	It feels hostile

👉 You check:

“Is that R… or just my C modifier?”

This prevents:
	•	unnecessary conflict
	•	projection
	•	escalation loops

⸻

